DLT and Blockchain / TC159 / Программно-аппаратные средства технологий распределенного реестра и блокчейн

Glossary - глоссарий терминов 
/main list of terms from [1] [307]/
1 address - [307] identifier for accounts participating in a transaction in a blockchain or distributed ledger network.
[NISTIR] a short, alphanumeric string derived from a user’s public key using a hash function, with additional data to detect errors. Addresses are used to send and receive digital assets.
[ME] most generally, this represents an EOA or contract, which can receive (destination address) or send (source address) transactions on the blockchain. More specifically, it is the right-most 160 bits of a Keccak hash of an ECDSA public key.
[MB] a bitcoin address looks like 1DSrfJdB2AnWaFNgSbv3MZC2m74996JafV. It consists of a string of letters and numbers. It’s really an encoded base58check version of a public key 160-bit hash. Just as you ask others to send an email to your email address, you would ask others to send you bitcoin to one of your bitcoin addresses.
1.2 account* [ME] - an object containing an address, balance, and nonce, and optional storage and code. An account can be a contract account or an EOA (externally owned account).
1.3 assert* [ME] - in Solidity assert(false) compiles to 0xfe, which is an invalid opcode, using up all remaining gas, and reverting all changes. When an assert() statement fails, something very wrong and unexpected should be happening, and you will need to fix your code. You should use assert to avoid conditions which should never, ever occur.
2 asymmetric key cryptography / public key cryptography - 
[NISTIR] a cryptographic system where users have a private key that is kept secret and used to generate a public key (which is freely provided to others). Users can digitally sign data with their private key and the resulting signature can be verified by anyone using the corresponding public key.
2.2 key* - see "cryptographic key".
[7816] sequence of symbols controlling a cryptographic operation (e.g. encipherment, decipherment, a private or a public operation in a dynamic authentication, signature generation, signature verification) ISO/IEC 7816-4:2013(en).
[29167] string of bits used by a cryptographic algorithm to transform plaintext into ciphertext or vice versa or to produce a message authentication code ISO/IEC 29167-10:2017(en).
[18000] privileged information that may be used, for example, to protect information from disclosure to, and/or undetectable modification by, parties that do not have access to this privileged information ISO/IEC 18000-4:2018(en)
2.3 cryptographic key* -
[13569] value that is used to control a cryptographic process, such as encryption or authentication ISO/TR 13569:2005(en).
[29167] string of bits of length given by key size that is used by the block cipher to transform some data block ISO/IEC 29167-21:2018(en).
2.3.1 key size* - [29167] number of bits in a data block that is an input (or output) of the block cipher.
2.3.2 block cipher* -  [29167] family of permutations that is parameterized by a cryptographic key and, optionally, the block size.
2.3.3 data block* - [29167] string of bits whose length is given by the block size of the block cipher.
2.4 asset(s)* [ISO 22739:2020] - anything that has value to a stakeholder.
[NISTIR] anything that can be transferred.
[25010] anything that has value to a person or organization ISO/IEC 25010:2011(en).
[19770] item, thing or entity that has potential or actual value to an organization ISO/IEC 19770-1:2017(en).
[24520] capital-forming goods used for the provision of the service ISO/TS 24520:2017(en).
[15686] whole building or structure or unit of construction works, or a system or a component or part thereof ISO 15686-5:2017(en).
актив - все, что имеет ценность для заинтересованной стороны.
2.4 BIP* [MB]; [ME] - Bitcoin Improvement Proposals. A set of proposals that members of the bitcoin community have submitted to improve bitcoin. For example, BIP-21 is a proposal to improve the bitcoin uniform resource identifier (URI) scheme.
2.5 big-endian* [ME] - A positional number representation where the most significant digit is first. The opposite of little-endian, where the least significant digit is first.
2.6 Bitcoin* [MB] - the name of the currency unit (the coin), the network, and the software.
[TC26] - (описание) для системы Биткойн можно установить следующие соответствия: система Биткоин – ИС с блокчейн публичная псевдонимная; тип реестра – реплицированный; майнер – уполномоченный пользователь ИС, который может являться как пользователем-валидатором (подтверждающим создание нового блока) или пользователем-контролером, так и в результате выполнения процедуры консенсуса – пользователем-регистратором ИС; любой пользователь системы – пользователь-контролер; биткоин/сатоши – условная единица; адрес (кошелек) – идентификатор пользователя; процедура прихода к консенсусу – с доказательством работы; ресурс пользователя-регистратора ИС – вычислительная мощность узла (пула) пользователя-регистратора, выраженная в количестве вычислений хэш- функции в секунду.
3 block(s) [ISO 22739:2020] - structured data comprising a block header and block data.
[NISTIR] a data structure containing a block header and block data.
[TC26] блок транзакций; данные, содержащие набор из одной или нескольких снабжённых отметками времени транзакций и, возможно, дополнительную информацию.
[ME] a block is a collection of required information (a block header) about the comprised transactions, and a set of other block headers known as ommers. It is added to the Ethereum network by miners.
[MB] a grouping of transactions, marked with a timestamp, and a fingerprint of the previous block. The block header is hashed to produce a proof of work, thereby validating the transactions. Valid blocks are added to the main blockchain by network consensus.
структурированные данные, содержащие заголовок блока и данные блока.
4 block header [ISO 22739:2020] - structured data that includes a cryptographic link to the previous block unless there is no previous block.
Note: A block header can also contain a timestamp, a nonce, and other DLT platform specific data, including a hash value of corresponding transaction records.
[NISTIR] the portion of a block that contains information about the block itself (block metadata), typically including a timestamp, a hash representation of the block data, the hash of the previous block’s header, and a cryptographic nonce (if needed).
5 block reward [ISO 22739:2020] - reward given to miners or validators after a block is confirmed in a blockchain system.
Note: A reward can be in the form of a token or cryptocurrency.
[NISTIR] a reward (typically cryptocurrency) awarded to publishing nodes for successfully adding a block to the blockchain.
5.2 block data* [ISO 22739:2020] - structured data comprising zero or more transaction records or references to transaction records.
[NISTIR] the portion of a block that contains a set of validated transactions and ledger events.
5.3 bytecode* [ME] - 
5.4 Byzantium Fork* [ME] - Byzantium is the first of two hard forks for Metropolis development stage. It included EIP-649: Metropolis Difficulty Bomb Delay and Block Reward Reduction, where the Ice Age (see below) was delayed by 1 year, and the block reward was reduced from 5 to 3 ether.
5.5 Byzantine Generals Problem* [MB] - a reliable computer system must be able to cope with the failure of one or more of its components. A failed component may exhibit a type of behavior that is often overlooked—​namely, sending conflicting information to different parts of the system. The problem of coping with this type of failure is expressed abstractly as the Byzantine Generals Problem.
6 blockchain(s) [ISO 22739:2020] - distributed ledger with confirmed blocks organized in an append-only, sequential chain using cryptographic links.
Note: Blockchains are designed to be tamper-resistant and to create final, definitive and immutable ledger record.
[NISTIR] blockchains are distributed digital ledgers of cryptographically signed transactions that are grouped into blocks. Each block is cryptographically linked to the previous one (making it tamper evident) after validation and undergoing a consensus decision. As new blocks are added, older blocks become more difficult to modify (creating tamper resistance). New blocks are replicated across copies of the ledger within the network, and any conflicts are resolved automatically using established rules.
[TC26] - см. "цепная запись данных".
[ME] a sequence of blocks validated by the proof-of-work system, each linking to its predecessor all the way to the genesis block. This varies from the Bitcoin protocol in that it does not have a block size limit; it instead uses varying gas limits.
[MB] a list of validated blocks, each linking to its predecessor all the way to the genesis block.
блокчейн - распределенный реестр с подтвержденными блоками, организованными в последовательную цепочку (блоков), созданный с использованием криптографических связей.
6.2 цепная запись данных* [TC26] - реестр, данные в который записываются блоками таким образом, что каждый новый блок включает информацию о предыдущем блоке.
7 blockchain system(s) - [ISO 22739:2020] system that implements a blockchain.
Note: A blockchain system is a type of DLT system.
7.2 system(s)* - 
7.3 blockchain network user* [NISTIR] - any single person, group, business, or organization which is using or operating a blockchain node.
7.4 user* - [19790] role taken by an individual or process (i.e. subject) acting on behalf of an individual that accesses a cryptographic module in order to obtain cryptographic services ISO/IEC 19790:2012.
7.5 network* - 
7.6 byzantine fault tolerant proof of stake consensus model* [NISTIR] - a proof of stake consensus model where the blockchain decides the next block by allowing all staked members to “vote” on which submitted block to include next.
7.7 centralized network* [NISTIR] - a network configuration where participants must communicate with a central authority to communicate with one another. Since all participants must go through a single centralized source, the loss of that source would prevent all participants from communicating.
7.8 chain-based proof of stake consensus model* [NISTIR] - a proof of stake consensus model where the blockchain network decides the next block through pseudo-random selection, based on a personal stake to overall system asset ratio.
7.9 checksum* [NISTIR] - value computed on data to detect error or manipulation.
7.10 conflict* [NISTIR] - one or more participants disagree on the state of the system.
7.11 conflict resolution* [NISTIR] - a predefined method for coming to a consensus on the state of the system. For example, when portions of the system participants claim there is State_A and the rest of the participants claim there is State_B, there is a conflict. The system will automatically resolve this conflict by choosing the “valid” state as being the one from whichever group adds the next block of data. Any transactions “lost” by the state not chosen are added back into the pending transaction pool.
7.11 идентификатор пользователя* [TC26] [ГОСТ Р ИСО ТО 13569-2007 (пункт 3.73)] - строка символов, используемая для однозначной идентификации каждого пользователя ИС.
7.12 пользователь информационной системы* [TC26] [ГОСТ 7.0-99 (пункт 3.1.31)] - лицо (группа лиц, организация), пользующееся услугами ИС для получения информации или решения других задач.
7.13 персональные данные* [TC26] [Федеральный закон No 152-ФЗ (статья 3)] - любая информация, относящаяся к прямо или косвенно определенному или определяемому физическому лицу (субъекту персональных данных).
7.14 регистрируемые действия пользователя* [TC26] - действия пользователя, информация о которых может быть внесена в реестр согласно политикам и процедурам ИС.
7.15 уполномоченный пользователь ИС* [TC26] - пользователь ИС, который в соответствии с политиками и процедурами ИС может осуществлять хотя бы одно из следующих действий с реестром: чтение, проверка, подтверждение, изменение.
7.16 пользователь-регистратор ИС* [TC26] - уполномоченный пользователь ИС, который в соответствии с политиками и процедурами ИС может производить внесение информации в реестр. Примечание: при PoW - «майнер».
7.17 пользователь-наблюдатель ИС* [TC26] - уполномоченный пользователь ИС, который в соответствии с политиками и процедурами ИС может осуществлять чтение реестра.
7.18 пользователь-контролер ИС* [TC26] - уполномоченный пользователь ИС, который в соответствии с политиками и процедурами ИС может осуществлять проверку корректности реестра.
7.19 пользователь-валидатор ИС* [TC26] - уполномоченный пользователь ИС, который в соответствии с политиками и процедурами ИС может осуществлять подтверждение корректности реестра. Примечание: в зависимости от политик и процедур ИС пользователь может исполнять различные функции. Например, в криптовалюте Биткойн все пользователи, имеющие доступ к блокчейн, являются пользователями-наблюдателями и пользователями-контролерами, майнеры являются пользователями-валидаторами, майнер, создавший блок, - пользователем-регистратором.
7.20 ресурс пользователя-регистратора ИС* [TC26] - количественная характеристика пользователя-регистратора ИС, зависящая от используемой в ИС процедуры консенсуса. Примечание: в ИС, использующих процедуру консенсуса с доказательством работы, под ресурсом пользователя-регистратора ИС понимается вычислительная мощность, выраженная в количестве решений некоторой задачи с заданным уровнем вычислительной сложности в единицу времени. В ИС, использующих процедуру консенсуса с доказательством владения – количество условных единиц, которыми в заданный момент времени может распоряжаться пользователь-регистратор.
7.21 chaincode /чейнкод* [TC26] - см. "умный контракт" (smart-contract).
7.22 blockchain developer* [BRCA] - any person or business, legal entity that creates, maintains, or disseminates software facilitating the creation or maintenance of a blockchain network or a blockchain service.
7.23 blockchain network* [BRCA] - any system of networked computers that cooperates to reach consensus over the state of a computer program and allows users to participate in the consensus-making process without the need to license proprietary software or obtain permission from any other user. The term includes, specifically, a public network of computers that cooperates to reach consensus over the state of a distributed ledger describing transactions in a digital currency.
7.24 blockchain service* [BRCA] - any information, transaction, or computing service or system that provides or enables access to a blockchain network by multiple users, including specifically a service or system that enables users to send, receive, exchange, or store digital currencies described by blockchain networks.
7.25 control* [BRCA] - the legal right, authority, or ability to obtain upon demand data sufficient to initiate transactions spending an amount of digital currency.
8 confirmed (transaction) [ISO 22739:2020] - accepted by consensus for inclusion in a distributed ledger.
[NISTIR] state of a transaction or block when consensus has been reached about its status of inclusion into the blockchain.
8.2 confirmed block [ISO 22739:2020] - block that has been confirmed.
8.3 confirmed transaction(s) [ISO 22739:2020] - transaction that has been confirmed.
9 consensus [ISO 22739:2020] - agreement among DLT nodes that 1) a transaction is validated and 2) that the distributed ledger contains a consistent set and ordering of validated transactions.
Note 1: Consensus does not necessarily mean that all DLT nodes agree.
Note 2: The details regarding consensus differ among DLT designs and this is a distinguishing characteristic between one design and another.
10 consensus mechanism [ISO 22739:2020] - rules and procedures by which consensus is reached.
10.1 consensus model* [NISTIR] - a process to achieve agreement within a distributed system on the valid state.
Also known as a consensus algorithm, consensus mechanism, consensus method.
10.2 процедура прихода к консенсусу* [TC26] 
10.3 round robin consensus model* [NISTIR] 
11 cryptocurrency [ISO 22739:2020] - crypto-asset designed to work as a medium of value exchange.
Note 1: Cryptocurrency involves the use of decentralized control and cryptography to secure transactions, control the creation of additional assets, and verify the transfer of assets.
[NISTIR] a digital asset/credit/unit within the system, which is cryptographically sent from one blockchain network user to another. In the case of cryptocurrency creation (such as the reward for mining), the publishing node includes a transaction sending the newly created cryptocurrency to one or more blockchain network users.
These assets are transferred from one user to another by using digital signatures with asymmetric-key pairs.
11.2 crypto-asset [ISO 22739:2020] - digital asset implemented using cryptographic techniques
11.3 currency* - 
11.4 digital currency* [BRCA] - a medium of exchange, a unit of account, or a store of value that is represented by entries in a distributed ledger generated by a blockchain network.
12 cryptographic hash function [ISO 22739:2020] - function mapping binary strings of arbitrary length to binary strings of fixed length, such that it is
computationally costly to find for a given output an input that maps to the output, it is computationally infeasible to find for a given input a second input that maps to the same output, and it is computationally infeasible to find any two distinct inputs that map to the same output
Note: Computational feasibility depends on the specific security requirements and environment.
[NISTIR] A function that maps a bit string of arbitrary length to a fixed-length bit string. Approved hash functions satisfy the following properties:
1/ (Preimage resistant) It is computationally infeasible to compute the correct input value given some output value (the hash function is ‘one way’).
2/ (Second preimage resistant) One cannot find an input that hashes to a specific output.
3/ (Collision resistant) It is computationally infeasible to find any two distinct inputs that map to the same output.
See the NIST SP 800-175B Guideline for Using Cryptographic Standards in the Federal Government: Cryptographic Mechanisms, http://dx.doi.org/10.6028/NIST.SP.800-175B.
12.2 function* - 
12.3 hash function*
12.4 Keccak256* [ME] - cryptographic hash function used in Ethereum. Keccak256 was standardised to SHA-3.
13 cryptographic link [ISO 22739:2020] - reference, constructed using a cryptographic hash function technique, that points to data
Note: A cryptographic link is used in the block header to reference the previous block in order to create the append-only, sequential chain that forms a blockchain.
13.2 cryptographic nonce* [NISTIR] - an arbitrary number that is used once. 
14 cryptography [ISO 22739:2020] - discipline that embodies the principles, means, and methods for the transformation of data in order to hide their semantic content, prevent their unauthorized use, or prevent their undetected modification.
15 decentralized system [ISO 22739:2020] - distributed system wherein control is distributed among the persons or organizations participating in the operation of the system.
Note : In a decentralized system, the distribution of control among persons or organizations participating in the system is determined by the system’s design.
15.2 decentralized network* [NISTIR] - a network configuration where there are multiple authorities that serve as a centralized hub for a subsection of participants. Since some participants are behind a centralized hub, the loss of that hub will prevent those participants from communicating.
16 digital asset [ISO 22739:2020] - asset that exists only in digital form or which is the digital representation of another asset.
[NISTIR] - any asset that is purely digital, or is a digital representation of a physical asset.
16.2 digest* [NISTIR] - see "hash digest".
17 digital signature - [307] data which, when appended to a digital document, enable the user of the document to authenticate its origin and integrity [ISO 14641:2018, 3.17].
[NISTIR] a cryptographic technique that utilizes asymmetric-keys to determine authenticity (i.e., users can verify that the message was signed with a private key corresponding to the specified public key), non-repudiation (a user cannot deny having sent a message) and integrity (that the message was not altered during transmission).
[ISO 7498-2] data appended to, or a cryptographic transformation (see cryptography) of a data unit that allows a recipient of the data unit to prove the source and integrity of the data unit and protect against forgery, e.g., by the recipient.
Note: Consider the definition ‘digital signature’ as “Data appended to data units, or cryptographic changes made to data units, which allows the recipient of the data unit to confirm the origin and integrity of the data and protect the data from being forged.”
distributed ledger - a type of ledger that is shared, replicated, and synchronized in a distributed and decentralized manner.
[ME] a short string of data a user produces for a document using a private key such that anyone with the corresponding public key, the signature, and the document can verify that (1) the document was “signed” by the owner of that particular private key, and (2) the document was not changed after it was signed.
17.2 signature* - 
18 decentralized application DApp [ISO 22739:2020] - application that runs on a decentralized system.
[ME] at a minimum, it is a smart contract and a web user interface. More broadly, a DApp is a web application that is built on top of open, decentralized, peer-to-peer infrastructure services. In addition, many DApps include decentralized storage and/or a message protocol and platform.
18.2 decentralized autonomous organization (DAO) [ITU SG17] - a digital entity that manages assets and operates autonomously in a decentralized system, but also relies on individuals tasked to perform certain functions that the automaton itself cannot.
[ME] - a company or other organization that operates without hierarchical management. Also may refer to a contract named“The DAO” launched on April 30, 2016, which was then hacked in June 2016; this ultimately motivated a hard fork (codenamed DAO) at block #1,192,000, which reversed the hacked DAO contract and caused Ethereum and Ethereum Classic to split into two competing systems.
[WTO] 
18.3 distributed application DApp [307] - application that runs on a distributed system.
19 distributed ledger [ISO 22739:2020] - ledger that is shared across a set of DLT nodes and synchronized between the DLT nodes using a consensus mechanism.
Note: A distributed ledger is designed to be tamper resistant, append-only and immutable containing confirmed and validated transactions.
[307] ledger that is shared and synchronized in a distributed manner.
распределенный реестр - реестр, который совместно используется набором DLT узлов сети (нод) и синхронизируется между данными узлами сети с использованием механизма консенсуса.
20 distributed ledger technology (abbreviated as DLT) [ISO 22739:2020] - technology that enables the operation and use of distributed ledgers. 
21 distributed ledger technology (DLT) account [ISO 22739:2020] - representation of an entity participating in a transaction.
Note: A smart contract, digital asset, or one or more private keys, for example, can be associated with a DLT account.
[307] representation of an entity whose data is recorded on a distributed ledger system.
21.2 DLT address [ISO 22739:2020] - distributed ledger technology address value that identifies a DLT account participating in a transaction.
21.3 DLT network [ISO 22739:2020] - network of DLT nodes which make up a DLT system.
21.3.2 distributed ledger network [307] - network within a distributed ledger system.
21.3.3 distributed network* [NISTIR] - a network configuration where every participant can communicate with one another without going through a centralized point. Since there are multiple pathways for communication, the loss of any participant will not prevent communication.
This is also known as a "peer-to-peer network".
21.4 DLT node [ISO 22739:2020] - node <distributed ledger technology> device or process that participates in a network and stores a complete or partial replica of the ledger records.
21.5 DLT oracle [ISO 22739:2020] - service that updates a distributed ledger using data from outside of a DLT system.
Note: DLT oracles are useful for smart contracts that cannot access sources of data external to the DLT system.
21.6 DLT platform [ISO 22739:2020] - set of processing, storage and communication entities which together provide the capabilities of the DLT system on each DLT node.
21.6.2 platform* -
21.7 distributed ledger technology (DLT) user [ISO 22739:2020] - entity that uses services provided by a DLT system.
[307] entity that uses services provided by a distributed ledger system.
21.7.2 user* - 
21.8 DLT system [ISO 22739:2020] - system that implements a distributed ledger.
21.8.2 system(s)* -
22 distributed system [ISO 22739:2020] - system in which components located on networked computers communicate and coordinate their actions by interacting with each other.
23 double spending [ISO 22739:2020] - failure of a DLT platform where the control of a token or crypto-asset is incorrectly transferred more than once.
Note: Double-spending is most often associated with cryptocurrency.
23.2 double spend (problem)* [NISTIR] - transacting with the same set of digital assets more than once. This is a problem which has plagued many digital money systems, and a problem that most blockchain networks are designed to prevent.
23.3 double spend (attack)* [NISTIR] - an attack where a blockchain network user attempts to explicitly double spend a digital asset.
24 entity [ISO 22739:2020] - item inside or outside an information and communication technology system, such as a person, an organization, a device, a subsystem, or a group of such items that has recognizably distinct existence.
25 failure [ISO 22739:2020] - loss of ability to perform as required.
25.2 fault tolerance [ISO 22739:2020] - ability of a functional unit to continue to perform a required function in the presence of faults or errors.
26 genesis block - [307] the first (nature) block in a blockchain.
27 hard fork [ISO 22739:2020] - change to a DLT platform in which new ledger records or blocks created by the DLT nodes using the new version of the DLT platform are not accepted as valid by DLT nodes using old versions of the DLT platform.
Note 1: If not adopted by all DLT nodes, a hard fork can result in a ledger split.
Note 2: In some contexts, the terms "hard fork" and " fork" are sometimes used for a ledger split that results from a hard fork of a DLT platform.
27.2 fork - [307] creation of different version of a distributed ledger originating from a common starting point with a single history.
27.3 ledger split [ISO 22739:2020] - fork creation of two or more different versions of a distributed ledger (3.22) originating from a common starting point with a single history.
28 hash value [ISO 22739:2020] - string of bits which is the output of a cryptographic hash function.
28.2 Hash chain* [NISTIR]
28.3 Hash digest* [NISTIR]
28.4 Hash value* [NISTIR]
28.5 hashing* [NISTIR]
28.6 hash rate (of a processor)
29 immutability [ISO 22739:2020] - property wherein ledger records cannot be modified or removed once added to a distributed ledger.
Note: Where appropriate, immutability also presumes keeping intact the order of ledger records and the links between the ledger records.
(Immutable [NISTIR])
30 interoperability [ISO 22739:2020] - ability of two or more systems or applications to exchange information and to mutually use the information that has been exchanged.
30.2 inter ledger interoperability [ITU SG17] - ability of two or more distributed ledger protocols to exchange information and to use information that has been exchanged with one another.
30.3 intra ledger interoperability [ITU SG17] - ability of two or more tokens within distributed ledger platform to operate with one another.
31 incentive mechanism* [NISTIR]
32 information / информация* [TC26] [Федеральный закон No 149-ФЗ (статья 2)]
32.2 external information / внешняя информация* [TC26]
32.3 internal information / внутренняя информация* [TC26]
33 information system / информационная система* [TC26] ([на основе ГОСТ ISO/TS 22220-2013 (п 3.4)] 
33.2 разрешенные механизмы ИС* (конфигурация ИС)* [TC26]
34 KYC* [MB] - know your customer (KYC) is the process of a business, identifying and verifying the identity of its clients. The term is also used to refer to the bank regulation which governs these activities.
[12812] process to verify the identity of a customer in order to prevent financial crime, money laundering and terrorism financing ISO 12812-1:2017(en).
35 ledger [ISO 22739:2020] - information store that keeps records of transactions that are intended to be final, definitive and immutable.
