49 password*
49.2 Key Derivation Function (KDF)* [ME] - also known as a password stretching algorithm, it is used by keystore format which to protect against brute-force, dictionary, or rainbow table attacks against the passphrase encryption. It repeatedly hashes the passphrase.
50 peer-to-peer [ISO 22739:2020] - relating to, using, or being a network of equal peers that share information and resources with each other directly without relying on a central entity.
51 permissioned [ISO 22739:2020] - requiring authorization to perform a particular activity or activities.
51.2 permissionless [ISO 22739:2020] - not requiring authorization to perform any particular activity.
51.3 permissions*
52 permissioned DLT system (permissioned distributed ledger system) [ISO 22739:2020] - permissioned distributed ledger technology system DLT system in which permissions are required.
53 permissionless DLT system (permissionless distributed ledger system) [ISO 22739:2020] - permissionless distributed ledger technology system DLT system that is permissionless.
54 private DLT system (private distributed ledger system) [ISO 22739:2020] - private distributed ledger technology system DLT system that is accessible for use only to a limited group of DLT users.
Note: Public and private categories apply to DLT users, and permissioned and permissionless categories apply to DLT users and those entities that administer or operate the DLT system.
55 private user distributed ledger system*
56 private key [ISO 22739:2020], [ISO/IEC 9798-1:2010] - key of an entity's asymmetric key pair that is kept secret and which should only be used by that entity.
[ME] the secret number that allows Ethereum users to prove ownership of an account or contracts, by producing a digital signature (see public key, address, ECDSA).
[MB] the secret number that unlocks bitcoin sent to the corresponding address. A secret key looks like the following: 5J76sF8L5jTtzE96r66Sf8cka9y44wdpJjMwCxR3tzLh3ibVPxh
56.2 (public key cryptography [NISTIR])
56.3 keystore file* [ME] - a JSON-encoded file that contains a single (randomly generated) private key, encrypted by a passphrase for extra security.
56.4 proof of stake consensus model* [NISTIR] / 
56.4.2 proof of stake [ITU SG17] - consensus process, where an existing stake in the distributed ledger system (e.g., the amount of that currency that you hold) is used to reach consensus.
56.4.3 процедура прихода к консенсусу с доказательством доли* [TC26]
56.4.4 delegated proof of stake (DPoS) - another approach to Proof of Stake where a set number of nodes are elected or selected to function as the block-producing full validating nodes for the network.
56.5 proof of work consensus model* [NISTIR] / 
56.5.2 proof of work [ITU SG17] - consensus process to solve a difficult (costly, time-consuming) problem that produces a result that is easy for others to correctly verify. 
Note: Producing a proof of work can be a random process with low probability so that a lot of trial and error is required on average before a valid proof of work is generated. Bitcoin uses the Hash cash proof of work system.
56.5.3 процедура прихода к консенсусу с доказательством работы* [TC26]
